WEBVTT

00:00.770 --> 00:04.315
Hello friends, I'm Rick Warren, and welcome to Spurgeon's Sermons.

00:04.775 --> 00:09.522
This is the official podcast brought to you by Premier and Spurgeon's College.

00:10.182 --> 00:18.353
You know the teachings of Charles Spurgeon have had a personal impact on my life in a profound way, and I'm confident they'll do the same for you.

00:18.473 --> 00:27.986
So get ready to be challenged, equipped, and guided by Charles Spurgeon, who is universally regarded as the greatest English preacher in the history of the church.

00:29.570 --> 00:35.656
the heroic in Christianity, a sermon by Charles Spurgeon, part four.

00:37.057 --> 00:40.481
For if ye love them which love you, what thank have ye.

00:40.541 --> 00:44.244
For sinners also love those that love them.

00:45.245 --> 00:50.050
And if ye do good to them which do good to you, what thank have ye?

00:50.931 --> 00:53.213
For sinners also do even the same.

00:53.253 --> 00:57.938
And if ye lend to them of whom ye hope to receive,

00:58.370 --> 00:59.572
What thank have ye?

01:00.393 --> 01:04.598
For sinners also lend to sinners, to receive as much again.

01:05.799 --> 01:09.484
Luke's Gospel chapter 6 verses 32 to 34.

01:09.664 --> 01:24.042
Read Luke's Gospel chapter 9 verses 54 and 55, and you will see that the Christian is to rise above human passion in the matter of gentleness.

01:25.905 --> 01:27.026
James and John

01:27.362 --> 01:36.513
When Christ was not received by the Samaritan villagers said, Wilt thou that we command fire to come down from heaven and consume them?

01:37.835 --> 01:44.262
But Jesus rebuked them and said, You know not what manner of spirit ye are of.

01:45.524 --> 01:47.066
And they went to another village.

01:48.808 --> 01:54.054
A Christian should be ready to give way, he should be quiet, peaceable, gentle.

01:55.436 --> 01:57.138
If in trying to do good,

01:57.378 --> 02:14.377
He wishes to bless certain people and they refuse to hear him, let him not grow indignant and denounce the offenders, but let him change the scene and carry his message to those who perhaps are hungering for it.

02:15.398 --> 02:21.625
He may go round again very shortly to those who repulsed him and find them in a better mind.

02:22.966 --> 02:24.268
Be gentle, brother.

02:25.169 --> 02:26.130
Soft words

02:26.210 --> 02:27.772
are hard to answer.

02:28.833 --> 02:32.057
They refused you at first, try them again.

02:32.117 --> 02:37.324
At any rate, be not provoked, for then they will have conquered you.

02:39.006 --> 02:41.990
Christians ought to be the gentlest beings under heaven.

02:43.652 --> 02:49.279
They are sent forth as lambs among wolves, and they are called to be harmless as doves.

02:50.480 --> 02:55.186
Such meekness will astonish and amaze their adversaries.

02:55.778 --> 02:58.763
and crown the religion of Jesus with honor.

03:00.105 --> 03:05.833
In the elevation of his or her joy, the Christian is also to rise above all other people.

03:06.735 --> 03:15.869
He or she may rejoice as they do in the common bounties of providence, but that joy is to hold very secondary rank.

03:15.889 --> 03:21.437
Even in their own success as a Christian worker, they take but measured satisfaction.

03:22.459 --> 03:24.722
Read Luke chapter 10 verse 20.

03:25.090 --> 03:28.033
and see what is the source of their truest delight.

03:29.314 --> 03:38.983
Notwithstanding in this, rejoice not that the spirits are subject unto you, but rather rejoice because your names are written in heaven.

03:40.585 --> 03:48.672
It is not a believer, a wonderful being, since even spiritual power and victory over the devil do not excite him.

03:49.813 --> 03:54.898
But they find their joy in a fact which is quite out of themselves and fixed

03:55.074 --> 03:57.356
by the unchangeable decree of God.

03:58.898 --> 04:04.143
The Christian is heroic, next, in his or her fearlessness.

04:05.364 --> 04:18.036
Turn to the twelfth chapter, verse 4, and there find Christ saying to his disciples, Be not afraid of them that kill the body, and after that have no more that they can do.

04:19.357 --> 04:24.082
But I will for warn you whom ye shall fear, fear him

04:24.162 --> 04:28.468
which after he hath killed hath power to cast into hell.

04:29.890 --> 04:38.581
The genuine Christian stands not in fear of public opinion and dreads not the frown of those whom God frowns upon.

04:39.943 --> 04:43.328
The true believer is to be willing to bear reproach.

04:44.569 --> 04:54.162
I, and to bear much more than reproach, as saints of God have done time out of mind, so far from flinching from suffering,

04:54.626 --> 05:07.582
We are not even to give it a thought as to how we shall speak if we are brought before kings and rulers, for a part of the Christian's heroism is to lie in his calm self-possession.

05:08.863 --> 05:11.647
See how the Lord puts it in the eleventh verse.

05:12.548 --> 05:24.402
When they bring you unto the synagogues and unto magistrates and powers, take you no thought, how or what thing you shall answer, or what you shall say.

05:25.122 --> 05:30.127
For the Holy Spirit shall teach you in the same hour what ye ought to say.

05:31.929 --> 05:40.898
The same man who is so gentle that if men will not listen to him he goes elsewhere is so steadfast that he cannot be silenced.

05:41.739 --> 05:53.170
Bold as a lion he stands before his accusers and he is not troubled as to how he shall put his words together, for he relies upon the indwelling spirit.

05:53.506 --> 05:58.773
whom the world cannot receive because it seeeth him not, neither knoweth him.

06:00.055 --> 06:10.290
Relying upon that spirit, he speaks when the time comes to speak, and it is the right word, as his adversaries are compelled to confess.

06:10.330 --> 06:16.078
Or he is silent, while it is time to be silent.

06:16.098 --> 06:21.746
And even in that silence, there is an awe which is felt by those round about him.

06:22.978 --> 06:26.261
after this fashion is he to play the man.

06:28.083 --> 06:43.779
See how far the true believer is lifted up above the world as you turn to Luke's gospel chapter 12 verse 22, where the Lord bids us to cultivate a holy ease of heart as to all temporal things.

06:44.980 --> 06:50.386
The rich man finds his wealth in his bursting barns, but the believer

06:50.754 --> 06:54.438
finds his treasure in the all-sufficiency of his God.

06:55.700 --> 07:03.469
The Savior says, Take no thought for your life what ye shall eat, neither for the body what ye shall put on.

07:03.509 --> 07:10.477
The life is more than meat, and the body is more than raiment.

07:10.497 --> 07:17.746
For all these things do the nations of the world seek after, and your Father knoweth that ye have need of these things.

07:18.594 --> 07:24.443
see, brethren, the Spirit of God is to lift us up above all fretful cares.

07:25.404 --> 07:45.255
We are to feel that the Father will provide for us in this world, and that Jesus will never leave us comfortless, because He is our shepherd, and we cannot want we are to dwell at ease and lie down in green pastures like a peaceful, restful flock.

07:46.537 --> 07:47.538
Coveredousness

07:47.650 --> 07:54.660
is not to approach us, for a man's life consists if not in the abundance of the things which he possesseth.

07:55.861 --> 08:07.677
The desire to heap together a vast mass of wealth prevents the enjoyment of that which is already gained, and this must not come near an heir of heaven.

08:09.179 --> 08:17.170
As to temporal things, we are to be constantly calm, content, grateful and trustful.

08:17.698 --> 08:20.222
relying upon the bounty of our God.

08:21.424 --> 08:33.443
This freedom from anxiety constitutes a main part of the Christian character and is so uncommon as to lift its possessor far above men of the world.

08:34.625 --> 08:42.418
Another point in which Christian heroism is seen is in humility and in delight in service.

08:43.938 --> 08:52.727
Turn to the 14th chapter and see our Lord's directions to His disciples, not to seek out the highest, but rather the lowest room.

08:53.768 --> 09:02.436
For, Seth, he, whosoever exulteth himself shall be abased, and he that humbleth himself shall be exalted.

09:03.818 --> 09:08.743
Habitually, a Christian man or woman is to have a modest esteem of themselves.

09:09.463 --> 09:11.986
They are never to be known as people who are forward,

09:12.226 --> 09:14.428
self-seeking and self-asserting.

09:15.610 --> 09:22.598
Men and women who are highly esteemed by themselves are seldom justified by the verdict of their fellow people.

09:23.919 --> 09:31.247
No, a Christian is to be one who is ready to do anything for the good of others, however lowly the service.

09:32.288 --> 09:34.911
She will wash the saint's feet.

09:34.931 --> 09:38.055
He will be a doorkeeper in the house of the Lord.

09:38.956 --> 09:40.978
If he may but serve his brethren,

09:41.346 --> 09:43.069
and glorify his master.

09:44.491 --> 09:47.395
Where are these Christian people asks a hearer?

09:47.756 --> 09:50.099
Where are these good and humble people?

09:50.360 --> 09:51.421
I cannot find them.

09:53.004 --> 09:54.606
Are you not one of them yourself?

09:55.848 --> 10:01.817
If you are not, make the confession and go before God and ask him to set you right.

10:02.618 --> 10:08.427
And when you are of a lowly loving spirit yourself, you will find others of a like mind.

10:09.649 --> 10:10.450
I must admit,

10:10.658 --> 10:23.373
that they are not easy to come at, but when you are meek and lowly, you will find them on the principle that like draws to like and birds of a feather flock together.

10:24.735 --> 10:37.650
That is not the Christian spirit which turns even the kingdom of heaven into an arena for ambition, but that man has the mind of Christ who becomes the servant of all for Christ's sake.

10:39.138 --> 10:48.187
That is not the Christian spirit which under the pretense of seeking liberty in the church, craves after lordship and self-display.

10:49.968 --> 10:56.915
Those who are under this influence will have no rule in the church of God except their own rule.

10:57.776 --> 11:04.222
They are too heady and high-minded to submit themselves to those who are over them in the Lord.

11:05.243 --> 11:08.946
The spirit of Christianity is lowly, yielding,

11:09.410 --> 11:12.833
easily to be entreated, seeking not itself.

11:13.994 --> 11:18.739
This is a chief point in the peculiarity of the peculiar people.

11:20.621 --> 11:26.987
Furthermore, there should be about the Christian a faith which there is not in any other.

11:28.148 --> 11:31.031
See Luke's Gospel chapter 17 verse 6.

11:32.012 --> 11:38.738
He should have an eye to see that which is invisible and an arm to lean on that which he cannot feel.

11:39.874 --> 11:47.562
He should act upon facts which others may accept as theories, but would never dream of risking a shilling upon it.

11:48.624 --> 11:59.375
Believers, ye are to be the men who can say to mountains, become planes, and to sycamore trees, be ye plucked up by the roots.

12:00.657 --> 12:08.946
You are to work miracles, not physical and material, but spiritual and mental, which are not less,

12:09.058 --> 12:13.585
but even more marvellous than the wonders of healing or resurrection.

12:15.248 --> 12:20.877
The next verse of this 17th chapter shows us that Christians are to be people of service.

12:21.498 --> 12:29.210
They are not to think that they came into the world to sit at a banquet, but they are to wait on their master while he sits at the table.

12:30.352 --> 12:36.402
Too many appear to consider that the services of the sanctuary are intended merely to feed them.

12:36.866 --> 12:44.418
They never look upon the house of God as a barracks for soldiers, or a place where workmen come together to sharpen their tools.

12:45.299 --> 12:56.337
They only regard it as a sacred restaurant, a spiritual larder, or a heavenly refectory, where much is to be received and little or nothing returned.

12:57.719 --> 13:04.690
O brothers and sisters, we must get out of the cramping influence of the spirit which makes even religion

13:04.930 --> 13:07.313
a selfish provision for ourselves.

13:08.254 --> 13:16.923
And we must scorn that skulking away from the trouble and fatigue which creeps over men of growing years and increasing wealth.

13:17.884 --> 13:21.789
We are to serve, not to recline at our ease.

13:23.110 --> 13:27.235
What are we that are so anxious to rest ourselves and benefit ourselves?

13:28.356 --> 13:33.842
The Lord Jesus Christ would not have us always be asking, How can I be happy?

13:34.370 --> 13:37.134
How can I obtain spiritual enjoyment?

13:38.195 --> 13:43.942
Servants are not supposed to spend their time in doing their own pleasure and seeking their own profit.

13:45.084 --> 13:52.233
A man's servant whose whole time was taken up with watching his own health would be of small value to his employer.

13:53.415 --> 13:58.882
Even so, we have something else to do beyond watching over our own inward feelings.

13:59.803 --> 14:02.066
To snatch a brand from the burning

14:02.274 --> 14:04.738
is better than to warm your own hands.

14:05.820 --> 14:15.455
To feed a hungry soul with the bread of heaven is a far higher deed than to eat the fat and drink the sweet yourself.

14:16.576 --> 14:30.418
There is more joy in plunging your arm up to the elbow in the mire to find a jewel for Christ than in washing one's own idle hands with the scented soap of respectable propriety.

14:31.874 --> 14:36.880
to get clean away from all idea of self-seeking in religion.

14:38.421 --> 14:50.795
We are first of all saved by grace, like drowning mariners snatched from the deep, but afterwards we are taught to man the lifeboat ourselves for the rescue of others from destruction.

14:52.157 --> 15:00.466
Christianity finds me a soldier wounded in battle and it heals my wounds, but it does far more than that

15:00.706 --> 15:12.585
It girds me with armor, it gives me a sword, it teaches me to fight, and it makes a hero of me if I yield myself to its full power.

15:12.605 --> 15:15.851
God grant it may do this for every one of us.

15:17.834 --> 15:19.116
Thank you for listening, friends.

15:19.396 --> 15:24.184
This podcast was brought to you by Premier in association with Spurgeon's College.

15:24.765 --> 15:27.890
